<br>
A new question then that I was truly intending.  If I choose to solo charm what is acceptable CHA to have to not be eaten alive by them always breaking mez in less than a minute.  I have tried with just one stien and seem like the mob was turning half-way through the first fight.  If I had both stiens then would last through the whole battle and maybe start second one before charm would ware off.<br>
<br>
Any thoughts would be appriciated.<br>
<br>
Mett 39 DE Enchanter <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccb9b><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub136.ezboard.com/beqenchantersrealm.showUserPublicProfile?gid=charmroxors>Charmroxors</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 56<br> <font color=#330000>(3/26/03 10:56:59 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub136.ezboard.com/feqenchantersrealmfrm11.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=169.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Question about INT vs. CHA</span><hr size=1> when i'm charm soloing, i equip the steins to get my CHA to roughly 235 ... i'm not doing any melee damage while charming so i dont need a weapon equipped, and you can afford to lose a few INT points if you're charming, you *shouldnt* be using as much mana as you would in a group... but that all depends on how much mana you spend buffing and debuffing.<br>
<br>
one other thing you might wanna note is that the checks a mob goes through to determine whether it will break charm or not are 1) its level versus yours 2) its magic resist 3) your CHA .... so if you attempt to charm something lower than you, you'll win the first roll, if he has a good MR, you might lose, meaning you should tash any mob you attempt to charm.<br>
<br>
=) happy charming.<br>
